Deep Dive into Apache Kafka

Kafka is not just a “message queue.”
It is a distributed commit log optimized for:

High throughput
Horizontal scalability
Fault tolerance
Real-time streaming
Event-driven architectures

Most companies use Kafka as:

Event bus
Streaming backbone
Buffer between systems
CDC pipeline
Real-time analytics layer
Log aggregation system
Async microservice communication layer
1. Core Kafka Mental Model

Imagine Kafka as:

Append-only distributed log files

Every event is:

written sequentially
immutable
ordered within a partition

Kafka is optimized around:

sequential disk IO
batching
compression
zero-copy transfer

This is why Kafka can do millions of messages/sec.

2. Kafka Core Components
Brokers

A Kafka cluster contains multiple brokers.

Broker = Kafka server node.

Responsibilities:

store partitions
serve reads/writes
replication
leader election

Example:

Broker-1
Broker-2
Broker-3
Topics

Topic = logical stream of events.

Examples:

user_clicks
payments
orders
video_events

Think:

Database table
but append-only and distributed
Partitions

Most important Kafka concept.

A topic is divided into partitions.

Example:

orders-topic
  partition-0
  partition-1
  partition-2

Each partition:

ordered
append-only
replicated

Ordering is ONLY guaranteed within a partition.

Offset

Every message has an offset.

partition-0

offset 0
offset 1
offset 2

Offsets uniquely identify messages inside a partition.

Consumers track offsets.

Producers

Applications writing data into Kafka.

Example:

app events
CDC connector
backend services

Producer decides:

topic
partition
key
batching
retries
compression
Consumers

Applications reading data.

Consumer reads:

partition
offset

Kafka does NOT push.

Consumers pull data.

Consumer Groups

Critical concept.

Consumers in same group share partitions.

Example:

8 partitions
4 consumers

Each consumer gets 2 partitions.

This gives parallelism.

3. Kafka Internal Architecture
Storage Engine

Kafka internally stores logs as files:

topic-partition directory

Example:

orders-0/
orders-1/

Inside:

log segments
index files
time index
Segment Files

Kafka splits logs into segments.

Example:

000000000.log
000001000.log
000002000.log

Why?

faster deletion
compaction
recovery
indexing
Sequential Writes

Kafka performance comes from:

Sequential Disk IO

Sequential writes are extremely fast compared to random writes.

Kafka relies heavily on:

OS page cache
append-only writes
Zero Copy Transfer

Kafka uses:

sendfile()

Data copied:

disk → network
WITHOUT user-space copy.

Huge performance gain.

4. Replication

Each partition has:

leader
followers

Example:

Partition-0
 Leader -> Broker-1
 Replica -> Broker-2
 Replica -> Broker-3

Writes go to leader.

Followers replicate.

ISR (In-Sync Replicas)

ISR = replicas caught up with leader.

Critical for durability.

Acks

Producer durability settings.

acks=0

Fastest.
No guarantee.

acks=1

Leader confirms.

Can lose data if leader dies before replication.

acks=all

Safest.
Wait for ISR replication.

Production recommendation:

acks=all
min.insync.replicas=2
5. ZooKeeper vs KRaft

Older Kafka:

depended on Apache ZooKeeper

New Kafka:

uses KRaft mode

KRaft:

removes ZooKeeper
metadata quorum inside Kafka itself
better scalability
simpler operations

Modern Kafka should use:

KRaft
6. Message Flow Internals
Producer Side

Producer accumulates records in memory batches.

Batch Example
batch.size=64KB
linger.ms=10

Producer waits briefly to batch more messages.

Benefits:

compression efficiency
fewer network calls
better throughput
Partition Selection

Producer partitioning:

No key

Round robin.

With key
hash(key) % partitions

Ensures ordering for same key.

Example:

customer_id

All events for customer go to same partition.

7. Consumer Internals

Consumers poll continuously:

poll()

Consumer fetches batches from brokers.

Rebalancing

When:

consumer added
consumer removed
partitions changed

Kafka redistributes partitions.

Problem:

pauses processing

Modern optimization:

Cooperative Sticky Rebalancing

Reduces movement.

